 the traditional questions about broadband, like availability and access, but also explores and evaluates new metrics more applicable to the evolving technologies of information access.Beyond Broadband Access brings together a stellar array of media policy scholars from a wide range of disciplines—economics, law, policy studies, computer science, information science, and communications studies. Importantly, it provides a well-rounded, international perspective on theoretical approaches to databased communications policymaking in the Americas, Europe, Asia, and Africa. Showcasing a diversity of approaches, this invaluable collection helps to meet myriad challenges to improving the foundations for communications policy development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBroadband communication systems. 0aTelecommunication policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aBroadband.  abroadband access.  adigital divide.  ainformation and communication technology (ict).  ainformation society.  ametrics.  apolicy.  auniversal service.1 aBauer, Johannes M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBohlin, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Justin S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlamm, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrieden, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Heather E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Sungjoong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Sangwon,